Grammar of Data Wrangling

Select, filter, mutate, arrange

Learning Objectives

  • Become more comfortable with the RStudio Interface.
  • Load and explore a dataset; work with individual rows and columns.
  • Practice recording written explanations and code chunks in an RMarkdown file and kniting the file into a report.
  • Learn the syntax for four useful data verbs: select, filter, mutate and arrange.

Today we begin with the fundamental building blocks of working with data in R.

Getting Started

Sign into Rstudio on JupyterHub. Navigate to the live-coding folder and open the file intro-to-data.Rmd.

As a reminder from our lesson “Hello World”, the lower left panel is called the Console where you can interactively execute R commands. The panel in the upper right contains your Environment, which will show you the variables and the datasets that you are currently working with.

R Packages

R is an open-source programming language meaning that users can contribute R code that make our lives easier, and we get to use them for free. In R, shareable code is called a package because it usually comes bundled with documentation, datasets, etc.

For this lesson, and many others in the future, we will use the following two packages:

  • tidyverse (an “umbrella” package which houses a suite of many different R packages for data wrangling and visualization, including ggplot )

  • openintro (data and custom functions from the text “OpenIntro Statistics” )

Let’s go ahead and load the packages in our interactive Environment using the library function in R. To do this, run the following two lines in your Console 1.

library(tidyverse)  #type this in Console
library(openintro)

Don’t worry if you see lines of text appear when you run these commands. They are not errors, but information that the package writers want to share with the user. For example, if you inspect the message produced by running library(tidyverse), you will see that 8 packages are loaded with this one call. As indicated in the picture below, each package contains R functions geared towards a specific task.

The lesson today will introduce you to four useful verbs from the dplyr package: select, filter, mutate and arrange.

The data

To begin exploring the functionality of R, we will work with a real dataset. Typically, analysts upload their own external dataset of interest with the Import Dataset button in the environment panel (datasets can be loaded from .txt files, .csv files, Excel files, etc.). However, many R packages have some great datasets that we can access directly once the package has been loaded.

One such dataset is called arbuthnot from the openintro package. This dataset contains the work of Dr. John Arbuthnot, an 18th century physician, writer, and mathematician. He was interested in the ratio of newborn boys to newborn girls, so he gathered the baptism records for children born in London for every year from 1629 to 1710.

To take a look at the dataset, type the following in the Console. 

View(arbuthnot)

One advantage of RStudio is that it comes with a built-in data viewer. This display should feel similar to viewing data in Excel, where you are able to scroll through the dataset to inspect it. However, unlike Excel, you will not be able to edit the data in this tab. Once you are done viewing the data, you can close this tab by clicking on the x next to its name in the upper left hand pane.

When inspecting the data, you should see four columns of numbers and 82 rows, each row representing a different year: the first entry in each row is simply the row number, the second is the year, and the third and fourth are the numbers of boys and girls baptized that year, respectively. Use the scroll bar on the right side of the console window to examine the complete data set. You can also use the triangles above each column of data to examine the values in the column in increasing or decreasing order.

Note that the row numbers in the first column are not part of Arbuthnot’s data. R adds them as part of its printout to help you make visual comparisons. You can think of them as the index that you see on the left side of a spreadsheet.

You can also see the dimensions of this data frame as well as the names of the variables and the first few observations by typing:

glimpse(arbuthnot)   #type this in Console

This command should output the following

## Rows: 82
## Columns: 3
## $ year  <int> 1629, 1630, 1631, 1632, 1633, 1634, 1635, 1636, 1637, 1638, 1639~
## $ boys  <int> 5218, 4858, 4422, 4994, 5158, 5035, 5106, 4917, 4703, 5359, 5366~
## $ girls <int> 4683, 4457, 4102, 4590, 4839, 4820, 4928, 4605, 4457, 4952, 4784~

which tells us there are 82 observations and 3 variables in this dataset. The variable names are year, boys, and girls and they are of integer type.

At this point, you might notice that commands in R look a lot like functions from math class; that is, invoking R commands means supplying a function with some number of arguments. The glimpse command, for example, took an argument \(x\) which was the name of a data frame. It has an additional argument width which defaults to the width of your console.

To learn more about the data, type the following in your Console:

?arbuthnot    #or help(arbuthnot)

Creating a reproducible report

Remember that we will be using R Markdown to to save your answers and work to the questions marked as Exercises.

Personalize the header by editing the author as we did previously. Generally, all code that is necessary for your solution should be typed in code chunks in your Rmarkdown document. Because View and help are used to explore the data interactively, they do not need to be included in your report.

As a reminder, You can execute the R code you type in code chunks by knitting the entire document. But often, you may want to run just the code chunk you are working on by running it from the Console. There are two ways to submit a single line of R code to the Console for execution:

  • place your cursor on the line of code and press Ctrl-Enter or Cmd-Enter at the same time, or

  • place your cursor on the line and press the “Run” button in the upper right hand corner of the R Markdown file.

Alternatively, if you wanted to run all of the R code in a given code chunk, you can click on the “Play” button in the upper right hand corner of the code chunk (green sideways triangle).

If at any point you need to start over and run all of the code chunks before a specific code chunk, you click on the “Fastforward” button in the upper right hand corner of that code chunk (gray upside down triangle with a bar below). This will run every code chunk that occurred before that code chunk, but will not execute the R code included in that code chunk.

Manipulating the data

Today we will learn about four verbs from the dplyr package that we can use to wrangle our datasets. They are select, filter, mutate and arrange. Each takes a dataframe as input and does something to it. Let’s see what each one does and how to use them.

Selecting a column

We can access the data in a single column of a data frame using the command:

arbuthnot$boys   #type in Console

This command will only show the number of boys baptized each year. The dollar sign basically says "go to the data frame named arbuthnot and find the column called boys. While the dollar sign is still commonly used in R, functions in the tidyverse package allow us to extract the same information in a different way.

Type the following command in the Console and run it:

select(arbuthnot, boys)    #type in Console

The first argument is the dataframe and the second is the column we want to select. The advantage of select is that we can select several columns at once, which we cannot do with the dollar sign approach.

select(arbuthnot, boys, girls) #type in Console

You may also have noticed a subtle difference in the way that R printed the data for the previous commands. For arbuthnot$boys, R printed a list of 82 numbers that were no longer displayed as a table. Objects that print out in this way are called vectors; they represent a set of numbers.

For select(arbuthnot, boys), R printed the first 10 rows of a table with 82 rows and 1 column. This is because when you call select(arbuthnot, boys), R actually creates a new, smaller data frame. This is common to all functions in the dplyr package.

What command would you use to extract the girls? Try it in the Console.

There are a variety of helper functions that make it easy to select large numbers of columns, and you will hear more about this later.

An important operator that we will discuss next is the pipe denoted by %>%. In short, it enables us to pipe an argument forward into a function, something along the lines of x %>% f rather than f(x).

As an example, when we type

arbuthnot %>% select(boys)    #type in Console

we are saying “take the arbuthnot dataset and supply it as input to the first argument of select function”. The main advantage of the pipe operator is that it allows us to string several commands together.

Filtering rows

Apart from select(), another useful function for subsetting a dataset is filter(). While select() lets us isolate columns of a dataset, filter() lets us isolate rows which satisfy certain attributes. Like select, the first argument is the data frame (which may supplied via the pipe operator) and the second states the criteria which must be satisfied.

What does the following line of code do?

arbuthnot %>% filter(year > 1685)  #type in Console

Try it in the Console!

The most commonly used logical operators for filtering are given below:

  • == means “if equal to”
  • != means “not equal to”
  • & means “and”
  • | means “or”
  • > means “greater than”
  • < means “less than”
  • >= means “greater than or equal to”
  • <= means “less than or equal to”

Write code to answer the questions below. Then run it and answer the questions in complete sentences immediately below each code chunk.

  1. How many boys were baptized in the year 1685.

We will now see our first example of piping two commands together. Suppose we want to know how often more than 5,000 girls were baptized. We first use filter to extract the rows that have girls \(>\) 5000. Then we go ahead and count the number of rows using nrow. This is shown below. Try it.

arbuthnot %>% filter(girls > 5000) %>% nrow()  #type in Console

For ease of reading, you may break up the code over several lines so each task is on a separate line.

arbuthnot %>% 
   filter( girls > 5000 ) %>%
   nrow()

When breaking up lines of code however, be careful to make sure that each line is syntactically incomplete, so R knows that there is more coming. For example, placing the %>% at the end of a line rather than the beginning of the next line does the trick.

  1. How often were more girls than boys baptized?

Don’t forget, we need to see both the code and also the answer to the question in a complete sentence.

Mutate new columns

The third verb we will learn about today is mutate. It enables us to create new columns in our dataset. For example, suppose we want to know the total number of baptisms in a year. To compute this, we could use the fact that R is really just a big calculator. We can type in mathematical expressions like

5218 + 4683

to see the total number of baptisms in 1629. We could repeat this once for each year, but there is a faster way. We can have R create a new variable for us, and we can define this new variable with a mathematical expression. Try out the following code in the Console:

arbuthnot %>% mutate(total = boys + girls)  #type in Console

This should print the desired dataframe (arbuthnot with the new total column). Take a look at the data in the data viewer. Has the column total been added to the dataset?

To add the new column to the dataset, you will need to assign the output from the previous command using the assignment operator <-.

arbuthnot <- arbuthnot %>%     #type in Console
                mutate( total = boys + girls)

You should see that there is now a data set called arbuthnot that has been loaded into your working environment. View it to see the new column called total that has been tacked on. You have changed the dataset using mutate!

Note: the new data set name can be anything you like, including the original name. Keep in mind that no matter what you call it, this is your local copy of the data set.

The following exercise only involves writing code. You should of course check that your code works by submitting it to the Console for execution and then taking a look at the data frame.

  1. Create and add a new variable ratio to arbuthnot which contains the ratio of boy baptisms to girl baptisms for each year. View the data to see which year had the largest boy:girl ratio.

Arrange in order

A large part of initial data exploration is examining the values taken by relevant variables. The verb arrange orders the rows of a data frame in increasing order by the values of selected columns.

For example, say we want to know the year with the most female baptisms. Conceptually, we would first sort your data set in decreasing order based on the girls column. You can do this interactively in the data viewer by clicking on the arrows next to the variable names. To include the sorted result in your report however you will need to use two new functions. First we use arrange() to sort the girlsvariable. Then we can arrange the data in a descending order with another function, desc(), for descending order. The sample code is provided below. Try it in the Console.

arbuthnot %>%
  arrange(desc(girls))   # type in Console
  1. Which year had the most boys being baptized? Use arrange and desc in a code chunk to find out.

Don’t forget, we need to see your code and also the answer to the question in a complete sentence.
